welcome to the fourth edition of the stanford seiu bargaining update in connection with stanford university's con page 1 issue 4 july 31 2009 from the stanford bargaining team welcome to the fourth edition of the stanford seiu bargaining update in connection with stanford university's contract negotiations with the service employees international union local 2007 seiu on july 7 2009 stanford and seiu began negotiations for a new collective bargaining agreement for approximately 1200 employees in schools and departments across the university including the slac national laboratory this weekly update which will be available during these negotiations will provide information about ideas and interests discussed options tentatively agreed to or other outcomes please disseminate the update as needed stanford and the seiu negotiations continue the parties stepped up negotiations in this fourth week and zeroed in on their priorities casting aside what can be characterized as wish list items while there remain a number of issues that will be a source of disagreement during these negotiations there also are a number of areas where the parties have found common ground in terms of emerging solutions those items include strengthening health and safety committees improving workplace safety establishing apprenticeship training classifications establishing a mechanism for determining alternative work schedules reforming the step increase structure and agreeing on a long term contract with reasonable wage increases in the out years of these common ground options the parties discussed their ideas around strengthening health and safety committees in addition to what they d like to see in connection with alternative work schedule provisions the small joint working group established to address issues related to the grounds and paint units of land buildings and real estate also reported progress and narrowed the potential options designed to address the current competitiveness of those units the small group discussed in detail an analysis of the outsourcing option and agreed to seek other alternatives such as consolidating specialist jobs into a generalist position modifying the groundskeeper assistant position at a competitive wage and creating a training classification the parties resume negotiations on tuesday august 4 2009 the agenda will include continuing the small group discussion regarding the grounds and paint units and reviewing supposals a hypothetical proposal related to health and safety committees and alternative work schedules the stanford bargaining team the stanford bargaining team includes david a jones director employee & management services human resources ann allison marsh senior manager employee & labor relations human resources cori bossenberry director of human resources school of medicine robert carpenter director of operations page 2 issue 4 july 31 2009 buildings and grounds maintenance land buildings and real estate megan davis associate vice president finance land buildings and real estate eric montell executive director stanford dining residential and dining enterprises and larry young director of human resources slac national laboratory
